Pagliacci is an opera set piece composed by Ruggero Leoncavallo in the late 19th century. The story is presented in the form of play within a play. It follows a troupe of travelling players on one of their tours. The lead player is a clown whose jealousy turns him into a murderer. In contemporary performances, the set organization, design, arrangement, and music seek to achieve originality in the the work.
The organization and arrangement of the opera at Missouri Southern State University adopts the classical themes ascribed to the artwork. The set is organized in a format that captures the traditional Italian village during the period during it was composed. The opera troupe is positioned below the center of the stage. This helps achieve the desired sound effect. Based on elaborate sound emissions, the emotional themes associated with the play emerge comprehensively. This enables the audience to develop a tacit connection with everything that happens on the stage.
The color scheme of the opera relies on a scheme of colored lighting that is used deliberately to achieve the desired mood. The set piece depicts the 19th century Italian style of architecture. The actors have two costume changes during the play. The first costume presents them as common people while the second one presents is used to play actors in the travelling theater. The character of Nedda is clad in flowery costumes and light make-up. This depicts her character as an attraction for the male characters in the opera. Canio, in his role as the troupe leader, is in traditional livery. This shows his status in the troupe he is as a leader. His portrayal as a clown is characterized by heavy make-up and colorful costumes. Tonio wears a rugged costume. This blends well with his role as he plays the fool. His make-up also includes a body suit that enables him become the hunch back. The set organization comprises of a comprehensive set piece which establishes the opera authenticity.
The prologue of the play comprises of bright colors. The introductory part features Tonio introducing the setting of the play. The audience is inspired to attach themselves to the emotions of the actors. Act one is set in the village. The common square and the tavern door are included in the set piece. This scene is composed of both bright and dark lighting, and colors. This helps depict the love scenes between Nedda and Silvio. Act two, on the other hand, is set on a stage. This is differentiated from the main stage where there will be playing the role of villagers. This act comprises of deep colors depicting the jealousy and murderous plot of the play. The coloring adopted is effective in portraying the callous theme ascribed to this act and draws the audience to develop emotions linked to these societal vices.
The opera takes place in the university. The singers are local as well as a cast comprising of Brian Cheney as Canio (Pagliacci), Ashley Wheat as Nedda, and Zeffin Quinn Hollis as Tonio. The opera is sung in Italian with English titles displayed above the stage.
The opera achieves its intended effect through the use of authentic costumes, set design, and elaborate music pieces. The costumes and make-up of the main actors help the audience empathize with the characters emotions and beliefs. The proper use of lighting and set arrangement creates thrill and suspense. The Pagliacci opera at Missouri Southern State University offers a great introductory experience to the opera novice. On the other hand, enthusiasts and critics are gratified by the performance because of its uniqueness.
